We notice a population imbalance, so now we merged with covariates so we can model on PC

totaldata=merge(combined_data,covs,by.x="ID",by.y="person_id")

dim(totaldata)
## [1] 225577     24
pcmod=lm(PRS~PC1+PC2+PC3+PC4+PC5,data = totaldata)
totaldata$predictscore=predict(object = pcmod,newdata=totaldata)
totaldata$residscore=(totaldata$PRS-totaldata$predictscore)
totaldata$Population=as.factor(totaldata$Population)

here are all the residualised scores

ggplot(totaldata, aes(x = residscore, y = Population, fill = Population)) +

We can scale the scores by all populatios jointly but note that SAS is depleted and EAS slightly enriched for high risk PRS:

totaldata$scaled_residscore=scale(totaldata$residscore)
ggplot(totaldata, aes(x = scaled_residscore, y = Population, fill = Population)) +
    geom_density_ridges(alpha = 0.7) +

Note that there are three choices for PRS, we can use :

  • the overall (unscaled) residual,

  • the scaled (overall residuals),

  • the population scaled residual

  • Here we use the populations scaled residuals

library(tidyr)
populations <- levels(as.factor(caddat$Population))
library(survival)
#Initialize an empty list for storing models and results
cox_models <- list()
glm_models=list()
for(pop in populations)
{
    print(pop)

#Subset data for the specific population
  pop_data_ldl<-ldldat[ldldat$Population%in%pop,]
  pop_data_cad<-caddat[caddat$Population%in%pop,]
  pop_data_ldl$PRS=pop_data_ldl$pop_scaled_prs
    
      
    print(paste0("population summary prs for population",pop))
    print(summary(pop_data_ldl$PRS))

    pop_data_ldl$sex=as.factor(ifelse(pop_data_ldl$sex_report=="Male",1,0))
  
    print(paste0("Sex_summary for pop",pop))
           
    print(summary(as.factor(pop_data_ldl$sex)))
  
    
      # Step 1: Linear Regression for LDL-C Levels
ldl_model <- lm(max_measurement ~ PRS + as.numeric(age) + as.factor(sex)+
                PC1+PC2+PC3+PC4+PC5+PC6+PC7+PC8+PC9+PC10,
                   data = pop_data_ldl)
  #summary(ldl_model)
  print(paste("LDL_coef_CI:",pop,":"))
print(round(confint(ldl_model,parm = "PRS"),1))

   prs_scale_factor <- 40 / coef(ldl_model)["PRS"]

  print(paste("population scale factor:",round(prs_scale_factor,1)))
          
          pop_data_ldl$scaled_ldl_prs <- pop_data_ldl$PRS / prs_scale_factor
ldl_model_2 <- lm(max_measurement ~ scaled_ldl_prs + as.numeric(age) + as.factor(sex)+
                PC1+PC2+PC3+PC4+PC5+PC6+PC7+PC8+PC9+PC10,
                   data = pop_data_ldl)

print(paste("LDL_scaled_coef_CI:",pop,":",ldl_model_2$coefficients['scaled_ldl_prs']))
    
  pop_data_cad$scaled_ldl_prs <- pop_data_cad$PRS / prs_scale_factor
  pop_data_cad$sex=as.factor(ifelse(pop_data_cad$sex_report=="Male",1,0))
  
  # Step 2: Cox or GLM  for CAD, again since age is time scale no need to use
  cox_model <- coxph(Surv(total_censor_age, total_pheno) ~ scaled_ldl_prs+as.factor(sex)+
                     PC1+PC2+PC3+PC4+PC5+PC6+PC7+PC8+PC9+PC10, 
                     data = pop_data_cad)
    ci=round(summary(cox_model)$conf.int['scaled_ldl_prs',],1)
    print(paste("HR_lci:",ci[3],",HR:",ci[1],",HR_uci:",ci[4]))
 glm_model <- glm(total_pheno ~ scaled_ldl_prs+ as.numeric(age)+as.factor(sex)+
                     PC1+PC2+PC3+PC4+PC5+PC6+PC7+PC8+PC9+PC10, 
                     data = pop_data_cad,family="binomial")
    
    log_or=summary(glm_model)$coefficients["scaled_ldl_prs","Estimate"]
    log_or_se=summary(glm_model)$coefficients["scaled_ldl_prs","Std. Error"]
    or=round(exp(log_or),2)
    lci=round(exp(log_or-1.96*log_or_se),2)
    uci=round(exp(log_or+1.96*log_or_se),2)
    print(paste(pop,"LCI:",lci,",OR:",or,";UCI",uci))

  cox_models[[pop]] <- cox_model
  glm_models[[pop]] = glm_model
}

names(glm_models)=populations

results <- data.frame(Population = character(),
                      OR = numeric(),
                      Lower = numeric(),
                      Upper = numeric(),
                      stringsAsFactors = FALSE)

for (pop in names(glm_models)) {
    model_summary <- tidy(cox_models[[pop]], conf.int = TRUE, exponentiate = TRUE)

    if ("scaled_ldl_prs" %in% model_summary$term) {
        term_row <- model_summary %>% filter(term == "scaled_ldl_prs")

        results <- rbind(results, data.frame(Population = pop,
                                             OR = term_row$estimate,
                                             Lower = term_row$conf.low,
                                             Upper = term_row$conf.high))
    } else {
        results <- rbind(results, data.frame(Population = pop, OR = NA, Lower = NA, Upper = NA))
    }
}
# # Create the forest plot using ggplot2

names(glm_models)=populations

results <- data.frame(Population = character(),
                      OR = numeric(),
                      Lower = numeric(),
                      Upper = numeric(),
                      stringsAsFactors = FALSE)

for (pop in names(glm_models)) {
    model_summary <- tidy(cox_models[[pop]], conf.int = TRUE, exponentiate = TRUE)

    if ("scaled_ldl_prs" %in% model_summary$term) {
        term_row <- model_summary %>% filter(term == "scaled_ldl_prs")

        results <- rbind(results, data.frame(Population = pop,
                                             OR = term_row$estimate,
                                             Lower = term_row$conf.low,
                                             Upper = term_row$conf.high))
    } else {
        results <- rbind(results, data.frame(Population = pop, OR = NA, Lower = NA, Upper = NA))
    }
}
# # Create the forest plot using ggplot2

print(results)

ggplot(results, aes(x = Population, y = OR, ymin = Lower, ymax = Upper)) +
    geom_point() +
    geom_errorbar(aes(ymin = Lower, ymax = Upper), width = 0.1) +
    coord_flip()+
    xlab("Population") +
    ylab("Odds Ratio (OR)") +
    ggtitle("Forest Plot of Odds Ratios for LDL-C PRS (per 40 mg/dL) on CAD across Populations") +theme_minimal()
